item.title: Doctors Investigate Link Between Rare Childhood Disease and Covid-19
item.description: Doctors in Italy and the U.K. have raised the alarm over a small but growing number of children displaying symptoms of a rare blood-vessel condition known as Kawasaki disease that may be linked to Covid-19.

item.title: Who Might Succeed North Korea's Kim Jong Un?
item.description: There is little doubt the next leader up would be a Kim family member, though the options look limited, with some analysts pointing to Kim Yo Jong, sister and confidante of the dictator, as a likely candidate.

item.title: Russia's Aging Infrastructure Threatens Oil Output Pact
item.description: Russia’s adherence to a hard-fought oil production deal with Saudi Arabia and the U.S. could be imperiled by its aging industrial infrastructure and the unique challenges of winding down a network of wells across its vast landmass.

item.title: China, South Korea Move to Revive Business Travel
item.description: South Korea says it has agreed with China to start facilitating some business travel between the two Asian neighbors, in Beijing’s first formal bilateral program to ease border controls.

item.title: Africa Braces for a Record Wave of Locusts
item.description: Flood waters that swamped bean and corn fields created a breeding ground for a swarm of desert locusts that destroyed a swath of farmland across eight East African nations earlier this year. Now their offspring are threatening a second wave of locusts, 20 times as large.

item.title: Both New Zealand and Australia Contained Coronavirus, but One Is Set to Pay a Heavier Price
item.description: The two countries’ different strategies to fight the pandemic appear to have delivered similar health outcomes, but the economic costs look likely to be significantly bigger in New Zealand thanks to its strict lockdown.
